---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'AboutPage',
  name: 'About World Radio Stations',
  inLanguage: 'en',
};
---
<Base
  title="About — World Radio Stations"
  description="A short story about the World Radio Stations project, why it was built and how it works."
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article class="legal container">
    <h1>About the project</h1>
    <p class="updated">A small independent project for radio from around the world, online</p>

    <h2>The idea</h2>
    <p>
      World Radio Stations is a free platform that brings radio stations from across the globe
      together in one place. The goal is simple: to help you find a great station in seconds —
      without digging through radio websites, without creating accounts, without ads in the
      music itself. We’re also working on an Android app that will be available soon.
    </p>
    <p>
      The app is aimed at listeners everywhere — whether you want to discover stations from
      another country or keep up with your home country’s radio while living or travelling abroad.
    </p>

    <h2>How it was built</h2>
    <p>
      The project is developed in our spare time, without outside funding and without ties to
      any particular media group or station. Running costs are covered by unobtrusive ad
      banners — nothing more.
    </p>
    <p>
      The web version you see on this site is the main way to listen — straight in your browser,
      no install. When the Android app is ready, it will add extra features like lock-screen
      playback.
    </p>

    <h2>Where the stations come from</h2>
    <p>
      The catalog is powered entirely by
      <a href="https://www.radio-browser.info" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Radio Browser</a> —
      an open, community-maintained database of radio stations from all over the world. This
      keeps the list always up to date: if a station starts broadcasting or changes its stream,
      it shows up here without any app update.
    </p>
    <p>
      The content itself — music, news, ads, talk radio — is broadcast by the respective
      stations and belongs entirely to them. World Radio Stations only forwards the stream to
      your device.
    </p>

    <h2>What we do NOT do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>We don’t store anything about you on a server — we have no user server.</li>
      <li>We don’t require an account, email or phone number.</li>
      <li>We don’t track what you listen to — Radio Browser statistics are anonymous.</li>
      <li>We don’t interrupt the music with ads — banners stay beside the player.</li>
      <li>We don’t resell any data.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Technical details</h2>
    <p>
      The Android app is in development — it will be written in Kotlin and will support
      lock-screen playback, MediaSession control with physical buttons and background play.
    </p>
    <p>
      The web player on this site is a static site built with
      <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Astro</a>, and it
      plays streams with native HTML5 audio. Your favorites and history are stored locally in
      your browser (localStorage) — they never leave your device.
    </p>

    <h2>Blog</h2>
    <p>
      On <a href="/blog">our blog</a> we publish articles about radio around the world, the music
      scene and useful tips for listeners. If you’re curious how internet radio works or want to
      discover new stations — take a look.
    </p>

    <h2>Get in touch</h2>
    <p>
      Have feedback, want to report a broken station or just say hello? Write to us on the
      <a href="/contact">contact page</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
